data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The configuration you used in .NET 10 (e.g., `CosmosEventId.SyncNotSupported` suppression) no longer prevents the exception.

All synchronous LINQ operators (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` now throw `InvalidOperationException` unconditionally—there is no workaround other than switching to async.

## The Fix

Convert to async equivalents:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

Key points:
- `Add()` remains synchronous (it only tracks in memory)—the await is on `SaveChangesAsync()`
- This is **async all the way up**; callers must also be updated to `await` these methods
- If you have interfaces (e.g., `IProductRepository`), update the return types to `Task<T>`
